Preheat your oven to 200°C. Remove the stalk top from the @aubergine{1} and slice into
1cm thick rounds. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1} into half moons.
Halve, then remove the core from the @bell pepper{1} and chop into 1cm cubes. Peel and
grate the @ginger{1} and @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the
@red chilli{1/4} lengthways, deseed and finely chop.

Mix a @salt{pinch}, the @pasanda style seasoning{} (add less if you don't like spice!)
and the @olive oil{2%tbsp} together in a large #mixing bowl{}. Add the aubergine and
onion and coat in the oil. Pop the aubergine and onion on a #baking tray{}, making sure
the aubergine slices don't overlap! Roast on the middle shelf of your oven until the
aubergine is soft and golden, ~{20-25%minutes}, turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, heat a glug of oil in a large #saucepan{} on medium heat. Add the pepper,
stirring frequently and cook until soft, ~{3-4%minutes}. Add the ginger and the
garlic. Cook for ~{1%minute} more. Stir in the @ground turmeric{2%tsp}, basmati rice,
water and @vegetable stock powder{1/2%pot}. Stir well to dissolve and bring the mixture
to the boil.

Reduce the heat to low and pop a lid on the pan. Cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove
from the heat and set aside (still covered) for another ~{10%minutes}.

> The rice will finish cooking in its own steam.

While the rice and aubergine cook, roughly chop the @coriander{1}(stalks and all).
Spoon the @Greek style natural yoghurt{150%g} into a small #bowl{}. Stir in half the
coriander and the @nigella seeds{1/3%tsp}.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and stir through a little of the coriander. Taste and
add some salt and pepper if necessary. Serve the Indian spiced aubergine on top of a
generous portion of golden rice and finish with dollops of nigella yoghurt and a
sprinkling of remaining coriander. Add some red chilli for a real kick. Enjoy!